    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">Create Guest Disk Storage</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal">EmulatR provisions disk images two ways: automatically at boot, driven by the platform manifest (<text styleclass="Code Example">create_if_missing</text>), and manually with the <text styleclass="Code Example">tools/mkdisk.py</text> generator. Both share one image-creation codepath and one geometry catalog, so a disk type&apos;s size is defined in exactly one place. A manifest references a disk <text styleclass="" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; color:#000000;">type</text>, not a raw byte count -- the size is resolved from the catalog at load.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Geometry catalog (single source of truth)</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">The authoritative geometry source is <text styleclass="Code Example">config/disk_types.json</text>, generated at build time from <text styleclass="Code Example">dec_disk_media_types.tsv</text>. Never hand-maintain both: edit the TSV, regenerate the JSON. Each type names <text styleclass="Code Example">total_lbn</text> and <text styleclass="Code Example">block_bytes</text>; capacity is derived (<text styleclass="Code Example">total_lbn * block_bytes</text>). A type is either a real DEC model (for example RZ28) or a sized blank target (for example blank-4G).</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
