    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Automatic provisioning (create_if_missing)</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">When a manifest storage entry names a missing image and sets <text styleclass="Code Example">create_if_missing</text>, EmulatR provisions a blank sparse image of the catalogued size on first boot. It never overwrites an existing image, and never provisions read-only media (an ISO is supplied, not created). Example manifest entry for the dqa0 ATA disk:</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">{ &quot;channel&quot;: 0, &quot;unit&quot;: 0, &quot;type&quot;: &quot;ata_disk&quot;,</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> &quot;media&quot;: &quot;dqa0.img&quot;, &quot;disk_type&quot;: &quot;blank-4G&quot;,</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> &quot;create_if_missing&quot;: true }</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">On first cold boot the run log reports the provisioning and the attach:</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">Storage: created blank disk image &apos;dqa0.img&apos; (4294967296 bytes)</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">attached ATA disk &apos;dqa0.img&apos; to IDE ch0 unit0</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Manual creation (tools/mkdisk.py)</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Use <text styleclass="Code Example">mkdisk.py</text> to pre-make a typed image outside the boot path -- a specific DEC model, or a sized install target. It calls the same core as <text styleclass="Code Example">create_if_missing</text>: looks up <text styleclass="Code Example">total_lbn * block_bytes</text> from the catalog, writes a sparse zero-filled file, refuses to overwrite without <text styleclass="Code Example">--force</text>, never creates for read-only media, and self-checks that the final size equals the catalog size.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">python tools/mkdisk.py --type blank-4G --out dqa0.img</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">python tools/mkdisk.py --type RZ28 --out dka0.img</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">The image written is BARE: exactly <text styleclass="Code Example">total_lbn * block_bytes</text>, zero-filled, with no partition table and no DEC disklabel. The guest OS install writes those structures. For the install path (boot the installer, install onto a blank target, boot the installed disk) a bare image is what you want.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Cross-platform sparseness</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Image creation uses a truncate-to-size, which is genuinely sparse on Linux ext4 (a 4 GiB image does not write 4 GiB physically). On Windows NTFS the file is lazily zero-filled and is not flagged sparse unless <text styleclass="Code Example">FSCTL_SET_SPARSE</text> is issued; <text styleclass="Code Example">mkdisk.py</text> sets it so behavior is identical on Windows and Linux. In practice the image costs nothing on disk until the guest writes to it.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
